Dropbox is a cloud-based file storage service that allows users to store and share files.
It provides a secure and reliable way to store and access files from anywhere, on any device.

Core Requirements / Functional
=================

(1) upload a file from any device
(2) download a file from any device
(3) share a file with other users and view the files shared with them
(4) Users can automatically sync files across devices

Non-Functional Requirements
===========================

Core requirement:
High available (over consistency)
Large as 50GB
Secure & reliable, able to recover file
Low latency

#Unlike stock, file might appear after a few seconds (CAP Theory)

For Dropbox, the primary entities are File(uploading, downloading and sharing)
FileMetadata(info like name, size, type, author)
user

API or Interface
================
POST /files for upload
Request:
{
  File,
  FileMetadata
}

GET /files/{fileId} -> File & FileMetadata for download

For sharing function, it might have an endpoint like this:
POST /files/{fileId}/share
Request:
{
  User[] // The users to share the file with
}

Query for changes to files on the server, wo need to know which file needs to be synced to the local
GET /files/changes?since={timestamp} -> ChangeEvent[]

Change Event includes the fieldId (change type), update meta data.

Tips
====
The user info will be passed in the headers (session token / JWT).


High level design
=================
Storing a file (1) file content (raw bytes) (2) metadata

For metadata, Nosql DB like dynamoDB can be used. DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL db hosted by AWS. Meta data is loosely structured
with few relations and the main query pattern being to fetch files by user. SQL db would work.

